[[Raymond Chandler]] (1888–1959) was an American-British novelist and screenwriter. He was born in Chicago, Illinois and lived in the US until he was seven, when his parents separated and his Anglo-Irish mother brought him to live near London; he was educated at [[Dulwich College]] from 1900.{{sfn|Marling|2000}}{{sfn|McCarron|2004}} After working briefly for the British [[Her Majesty's Civil Service|Civil Service]], he became a part-time teacher at Dulwich, supplementing his income as a journalist and writer—mostly for ''[[The Westminster Gazette]]'' and ''[[The Academy (periodical)|The Academy]]''.{{sfn|McCarron|2004}} His output—consisting largely of poems and essays—was not to his taste, and his biographer Paul Bishop considers the work as "lifeless", while ''[[Contemporary Authors]]'' describes it as "lofty in subject and mawkish in tone".<ref name="Gage CA" /> Chandler returned to the US in 1912 where he trained to become an accountant in Los Angeles.{{sfn|Williams|2012|pp=57–57}} In 1917 he enlisted in the [[Canadian Expeditionary Force]], saw combat in the trenches in France where he was wounded, and was undergoing flight training in the fledgling [[Royal Air Force]] when the war ended.{{sfn|Williams|2012|pp=67–68}}

Chandler returned to the US in 1919 to rekindle his literary career, but instead took a job with an oil company until he was fired in 1932 following a bout of depression, womanizing and heavy drinking.{{sfn|McCarron|2004}} He began writing crime stories for the [[pulp magazine]]s ''[[Black Mask (magazine)|Black Mask]]'', ''Detective Fiction Weekly'', ''The Fortnightly Intruder'' and ''Dime Detective''.{{sfn|Marling|2000}} The stories were subsequently brought together in collected editions.{{sfn|Macleod|1988|p=6}} In 1939, at the behest of the publisher [[Alfred A. Knopf, Sr.]], Chandler wrote his first novel, ''[[The Big Sleep]]'', for which he used parts of his short stories "Killer in the Rain" (1935) and "The Curtain" (1936).{{sfn|Durham|1972|p=viii}}{{sfn|Williams|2012|pp=142–43}} He went on to write seven novels, many of which featured the character [[Philip Marlowe]].<ref name="Gage CA" />

In 1944 Chandler was asked by [[Paramount Pictures]] to write the script for the film ''[[Double Indemnity (film)|Double Indemnity]]'' with [[Billy Wilder]]; the film was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]].{{sfn|Macleod|1988|pp=197–98}} It was the first of seven scripts Chandler wrote, although two of them were unused.{{sfn|Bruccoli|1979|pp=135–36}} In 1959 Chandler died of pneumonia, brought on by alcoholism.{{sfn|McCarron|2004}} In the aftermath of his death, many of his unpublished writings—including letters, literary criticism and prose and poetry—were released. His biographer Tom Williams considers that Chandler's name has become "a touchstone for crime writing, representing not just excellent fiction, but also a type of writing that is at once powerful and beautiful."{{sfn|Williams|2012|p=348}}

==Publications in periodicals and newspapers==
"The Rose Leaf Romance" and "Organ Music" are two early short stories that were included in a collection, but their first printing is unknown.{{sfn|Bruccoli|1979|p=115}}

